    <h1 id="great-blue-heron-behavior-solitary-hunter-social-breeder">Great Blue Heron Behavior: Solitary Hunter, Social Breeder</h1>
<p>The Great Blue Heron lives a double life. For most of the year it is a loner that defends exclusive fishing grounds; for a few months it becomes a colonist, nesting shoulder-to-shoulder with hundreds of neighbors. Understanding that switch is the key to understanding the species.</p>
<h2 id="the-solitary-season">The solitary season</h2>
<p>Outside the breeding season, Great Blue Herons forage alone and defend feeding territories against other herons with dramatic threat displays: the defender approaches an intruder with its head thrown back, wings outstretched, and bill pointed skyward. Gulls — and occasionally humans — can be targets of the same maneuver.<sup id="fnref:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup> Where food is superabundant, spacing relaxes and birds tolerate company, but the default is one heron, one fishing spot.<sup id="fnref:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup> Along one Virginia stream, observers noted a heron staked out roughly every 100 yards.<sup id="fnref:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></p>
<p>Activity peaks around <strong>dawn and dusk</strong>, though herons feed both day and night, and roost communally at night — typically in groups of 5–20 birds in tall, sturdy trees.<sup id="fnref:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup><sup id="fnref:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup> They are famously still: a hunting heron may barely move for an hour, conserving energy for a single decisive strike.<sup id="fnref:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="the-social-season">The social season</h2>
<p>At the colony, the same birds become elaborately social. Males arrive first and claim nest sites, then court passing females with neck-stretching, plume-fluffing, bill-snapping displays and circular flights over the colony.<sup id="fnref:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup> Once paired, birds greet each other with ritualized ceremonies — twining necks, clattering bills, exchanging sticks, and performing nest-relief displays with erected plumes.<sup id="fnref2:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup> Colonies can hold several hundred pairs, with multiple nests in a single tree 100 feet or more off the ground.<sup id="fnref:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup></p>
<p>Herons are <strong>seasonally monogamous</strong>: faithful within a breeding season, but most choose new mates each year, and most males pick a different nest each season.<sup id="fnref:9"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:9">9</a></sup> Colonies themselves are dynamic — they may persist for 20+ years or relocate after disturbance, and adults often return to nest in the same colony where they were born.<sup id="fnref:10"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:10">10</a></sup><sup id="fnref:11"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:11">11</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="defense-and-danger-behavior">Defense and danger behavior</h2>
<p>Away from nests, adult herons rely on size and a dagger bill that makes them "high-risk" prey; few predators attempt them.<sup id="fnref:12"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:12">12</a></sup> At nests, though, parents are famously pragmatic: confronted by a Great Horned Owl or eagle, a parent will often stand aside or fly off rather than fight — prioritizing its own survival to breed another day — though exceptions exist, including a filmed case of a heron screaming down an attacking owl until it left.<sup id="fnref:13"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:13">13</a></sup> When a colony suffers a predation event or repeated human intrusion, the birds may abandon the site entirely, eggs and chicks included.<sup id="fnref2:12"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:12">12</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="quirks-worth-knowing">Quirks worth knowing</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bill-clapping</strong>: both sexes snap their bill tips together in territorial and breeding displays.<sup id="fnref:14"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:14">14</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Winter scavenging</strong>: Utah herons have learned to steal or scavenge fish from Common Goldeneyes diving in small pockets of open water.<sup id="fnref:15"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:15">15</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>"Nest hopping"</strong>: large chicks sometimes clamber between neighboring nests in a crowded colony.<sup id="fnref:16"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:16">16</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Weather tolerance</strong>: parents sit tight on eggs through late-winter snowstorms; feathers shed rain remarkably well, aided by powder-down grooming.<sup id="fnref:17"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:17">17</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Water landings and swims</strong>: though rarely seen, herons can swim and will land briefly on water.<sup id="fnref:18"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:18">18</a></sup></li>
</ul>
